# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: barcode-of-life-data-system
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/african-society-for-bioinformatics-and-computational-biology] The **African Society for Bioinformatics and Computational Biology** (**ASBCB**) is a non-profit professional association dedicated to the advancement of bioinformatics and computational biology in Africa.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/african-society-for-bioinformatics-and-computational-biology] ASBCB was established in February 2004 at a meeting in Cape Town, South Africa.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/african-society-for-bioinformatics-and-computational-biology] The Society serves as an international forum and resource devoted to developing competence and expertise in bioinformatics and computational biology in Africa.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/african-society-for-bioinformatics-and-computational-biology] It complements its activities with those of other international and national societies, associations and institutions, public and private, that have similar aims.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/african-society-for-bioinformatics-and-computational-biology] It also promotes the standing of African bioinformatics and computational biology in the global arena through liaison and cooperation with other international bodies.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/african-society-for-bioinformatics-and-computational-biology] It is an affiliated regional group of the International Society for Computational Biology (ISCB).
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/african-society-for-bioinformatics-and-computational-biology] The ASBCB supports the development of bioiniformatics and computational biology at a national level across Africa, including in Ghana, Nigeria, South Africa and Zimbabwe.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/african-society-for-bioinformatics-and-computational-biology] Many of the most important applications of bioininformatics and computational biology in Africa relate to human genetic diversity, which does not match national boundaries.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/african-society-for-bioinformatics-and-computational-biology] The ASBCB supports international projects with this focus, such as the H3ABioNet network.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/african-society-for-bioinformatics-and-computational-biology] H3ABioNet has also supported Introduction to Bionformatics Training(IBT) courses delivered remotely across Africa.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/african-society-for-bioinformatics-and-computational-biology] In conjunction with other panAfrican initiatives such as the African BioGenome Project the ASBCB supports initiatives needed to increase bioinformatics resources in Africa.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/african-society-for-bioinformatics-and-computational-biology] The ASBCB has extablished six Communities of Special Interest (COSIs) which reflect the different specialisations of members of the organisation, as well as emphasizing topics particularly relevant to Africa.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/african-society-for-bioinformatics-and-computational-biology] Since 2007 it has been hosting the ISCB Africa ASBCB Conference on Bioinformatics at different locations in Africa to bring together scientists working in bioinformatics from different African nations together with other international researchers in the field.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/australia-bioinformatics-resource] The **Australia Bioinformatics Resource** (**EMBL-ABR**) (formerly the **Bioinformatics Resource Australia - EMBL** (**BRAEMBL**)) was a significant initiative under the associate membership to EMBL.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/australia-bioinformatics-resource] Since 2019, all activities carried out under EMBL-ABR have rolled over into the Bioplatforms Australia (NCRIS-funded) Australian BioCommons, under new funding agreements and led by Associate Professor Andrew Lonie.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/australia-bioinformatics-resource] EMBL-ABR was supported by Bioplatforms Australia and the University of Melbourne.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/australia-bioinformatics-resource] EMBL-ABR Hub was hosted at the Victorian Life Sciences Computation Initiative (VLSCI) at the University of Melbourne.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/australia-bioinformatics-resource] In July 2016, EMBL-ABR announced an agreement to collaborate with GOBLET to develop training programs for bioinformatics.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/barcode-of-life-data-system] The **Barcode of Life Data System** (commonly known as **BOLD** or **BOLDSystems**) is a web platform specifically devoted to DNA barcoding.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/barcode-of-life-data-system] It is a cloud-based data storage and analysis platform developed at the Centre for Biodiversity Genomics in Canada.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/barcode-of-life-data-system] It consists of four main modules, a data portal, an educational portal, a registry of BINs (putative species), and a data collection and analysis workbench which provides an online platform for analyzing DNA sequences.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/barcode-of-life-data-system] Since its launch in 2005, BOLD has been extended to provide a range of functionality including data organization, validation, visualization and publication.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/barcode-of-life-data-system] The most recent version of the system, version 5, launched in 2024.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/barcode-of-life-data-system] Version 4, launched in 2017, brought a set of improvements supporting data collection and analysis but also included novel functionality improving data dissemination, citation, and annotation.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/barcode-of-life-data-system] Before November 16, 2020, BOLD already contained barcode sequences for 318,105 formally described species covering animals, plants, fungi, protists (with ~8.9 million specimens).
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/barcode-of-life-data-system] Data release of BOLD mainly originated from a project BARCODE 500K executed by the International Barcode of Life (iBOL) Consortium from 2010 to 2015.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/barcode-of-life-data-system] It aimed for data acquisition of DNA barcode records for 5M specimens representing 500K species.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/barcode-of-life-data-system] All the specimens collection, sequences assignment, information sorting are contributed by great amount of scientists, collaborators and facilities from nations over the world.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/barcode-of-life-data-system] Data accumulation increases the accuracy of DNA barcode identification and facilitates the attainment of barcoding of life.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/bioinformatics] Computational, statistical, and computer programming techniques have been used for computer simulation analyses of biological queries.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/bioinformatics] They include reused specific analysis "pipelines", particularly in the field of genomics, such as by the identification of genes and single nucleotide polymorphisms (SNPs).
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/bioinformatics] These pipelines are used to better understand the genetic basis of disease, unique adaptations, desirable properties (especially in agricultural species), or differences between populations.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/bioinformatics] Bioinformatics also includes proteomics, which aims to understand the organizational principles within nucleic acid and protein sequences.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/bioinformatics] Image and signal processing allow the extraction of useful results from large amounts of raw data.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/bioinformatics] It aids in sequencing and annotating genomes and their observed mutations.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/bioinformatics] Bioinformatics includes text mining of biological literature and the development of biological and gene ontologies to organize and query biological data.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/bioinformatics] It also plays a role in the analysis of gene and protein expression and regulation.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/bioinformatics] Bioinformatic tools aid in comparing, analyzing, and interpreting genetic and genomic data and in the understanding of evolutionary aspects of molecular biology.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/bioinformatics] At a more integrative level, it helps analyze and catalogue the biological pathways and networks that are an important part of systems biology.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/bioinformatics] In structural biology, it aids in the simulation and modeling of DNA, RNA, proteins as well as biomolecular interactions.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/bioinformatics] The first definition of the term *bioinformatics* was coined by Paulien Hogeweg and Ben Hesper in 1970, to refer to the study of information processes in biotic systems.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/bioinformatics] This definition placed bioinformatics as a field parallel to biochemistry (the study of chemical processes in biological systems).
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/bioinformatics] Bioinformatics and computational biology involved the analysis of biological data, particularly DNA, RNA, and protein sequences.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/bioinformatics] The field of bioinformatics experienced explosive growth starting in the mid-1990s, driven largely by the Human Genome Project and by rapid advances in DNA sequencing technology.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/bioinformatics] Analyzing biological data to produce meaningful information involves writing and running software programs that use algorithms from graph theory, artificial intelligence, soft computing, data mining, image processing, and computer simulation.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/bioinformatics] The algorithms in turn depend on theoretical foundations such as discrete mathematics, control theory, system theory, information theory, and statistics.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/bioinformatics] There has been a tremendous advance in speed and cost reduction since the completion of the Human Genome Project, with some labs able to sequence over 100,000 billion bases each year, and a full genome can be sequenced for $1,000 or less.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/bioinformatics] Computers became essential in molecular biology when protein sequences became available after Frederick Sanger determined the sequence of insulin in the early 1950s.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/bioinformatics] Comparing multiple sequences manually turned out to be impractical.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/bioinformatics] Margaret Oakley Dayhoff, a pioneer in the field, compiled one of the first protein sequence databases, initially published as books as well as methods of sequence alignment and molecular evolution.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/bioinformatics] Another early contributor to bioinformatics was Elvin A.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/bioinformatics] Kabat, who pioneered biological sequence analysis in 1970 with his comprehensive volumes of antibody sequences released online with Tai Te Wu between 1980 and 1991.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/bioinformatics] In the 1970s, new techniques for sequencing DNA were applied to bacteriophage MS2 and øX174, and the extended nucleotide sequences were then parsed with informational and statistical algorithms.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/bioinformatics] These studies illustrated that well known features, such as the coding segments and the triplet code, are revealed in straightforward statistical analyses and were the proof of the concept that bioinformatics would be insightful.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/bioinformatics] In order to study how normal cellular activities are altered in different disease states, raw biological data must be combined to form a comprehensive picture of these activities.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/bioinformatics] Therefore, the field of bioinformatics has evolved such that the most pressing task now involves the analysis and interpretation of various types of data.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/bioinformatics] This also includes nucleotide and amino acid sequences, protein domains, and protein structures.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/bioinformatics] The primary goal of bioinformatics is to increase the understanding of biological processes.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/bioinformatics] What sets it apart from other approaches is its focus on developing and applying computationally intensive techniques to achieve this goal.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/bioinformatics] Examples include: pattern recognition, data mining, machine learning algorithms, and visualization.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/bioinformatics] Bioinformatics entails the creation and advancement of databases, algorithms, computational and statistical techniques, and theory to solve formal and practical problems arising from the management and analysis of biological data.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/bioinformatics] Over the past few decades, rapid developments in genomic and other molecular research technologies and developments in information technologies have combined to produce a tremendous amount of information related to molecular biology.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/bioinformatics] Bioinformatics is the name given to these mathematical and computing approaches used to glean understanding of biological processes.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/bioinformatics] Common activities in bioinformatics include mapping and analyzing DNA and protein sequences, aligning DNA and protein sequences to compare them, and creating and viewing 3-D models of protein structures.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/bioinformatics] Since the bacteriophage Phage Φ-X174 was sequenced in 1977, the DNA sequences of thousands of organisms have been decoded and stored in databases.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/bioinformatics] This sequence information is analyzed to determine genes that encode proteins, RNA genes, regulatory sequences, structural motifs, and repetitive sequences.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/bioinformatics] A comparison of genes within a species or between different species can show similarities between protein functions, or relations between species (the use of molecular systematics to construct phylogenetic trees).
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/bioinformatics] With the growing amount of data, it long ago became impractical to analyze DNA sequences manually.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/bioinformatics] Computer programs such as BLAST are used routinely to search sequences—as of 2008, from more than 260,000 organisms, containing over 190 billion nucleotides.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/bioinformatics] Before sequences can be analyzed, they are obtained from a data storage bank, such as GenBank.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/bioinformatics] DNA sequencing is still a non-trivial problem as the raw data may be noisy or affected by weak signals.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/bioinformatics] Algorithms have been developed for base calling for the various experimental approaches to DNA sequencing.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/bioinformatics] Most DNA sequencing techniques produce short fragments of sequence that need to be assembled to obtain complete gene or genome sequences.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/bioinformatics] The shotgun sequencing technique (used by The Institute for Genomic Research (TIGR) to sequence the first bacterial genome, *Haemophilus influenzae*) generates the sequences of many thousands of small DNA fragments (ranging from 35 to 900 nucleotides long, depending on the sequencing technology).
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/bioinformatics] The ends of these fragments overlap and, when aligned properly by a genome assembly program, can be used to reconstruct the complete genome.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/bioinformatics] Shotgun sequencing yields sequence data quickly, but the task of assembling the fragments can be quite complicated for larger genomes.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/bioinformatics] For a genome as large as the human genome, it may take many days of CPU time on large-memory, multiprocessor computers to assemble the fragments, and the resulting assembly usually contains numerous gaps that must be filled in later.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/bioinformatics] Shotgun sequencing is the method of choice for virtually all genomes sequenced (rather than chain-termination or chemical degradation methods), and genome assembly algorithms are a critical area of bioinformatics research.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/bioinformatics] In genomics, annotation refers to the process of marking the stop and start regions of genes and other biological features in a sequenced DNA sequence.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/bioinformatics] Many genomes are too large to be annotated by hand.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/bioinformatics] As the rate of sequencing exceeds the rate of genome annotation, genome annotation has become the new bottleneck in bioinformatics.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/bioinformatics] Genome annotation can be classified into three levels: the nucleotide, protein, and process levels.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/bioinformatics] Gene finding is a chief aspect of nucleotide-level annotation.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/bioinformatics] For complex genomes, a combination of ab initio gene prediction and sequence comparison with expressed sequence databases and other organisms can be successful.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/bioinformatics] Nucleotide-level annotation also allows the integration of genome sequence with other genetic and physical maps of the genome.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/bioinformatics] The principal aim of protein-level annotation is to assign function to the protein products of the genome.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/bioinformatics] Databases of protein sequences and functional domains and motifs are used for this type of annotation.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/bioinformatics] About half of the predicted proteins in a new genome sequence tend to have no obvious function.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/bioinformatics] Understanding the function of genes and their products in the context of cellular and organismal physiology is the goal of process-level annotation.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/bioinformatics] An obstacle of process-level annotation has been the inconsistency of terms used by different model systems.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/bioinformatics] The Gene Ontology Consortium is helping to solve this problem.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/bioinformatics] The first description of a comprehensive annotation system was published in 1995 by The Institute for Genomic Research, which performed the first complete sequencing and analysis of the genome of a free-living (non-symbiotic) organism, the bacterium *Haemophilus influenzae*.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/bioinformatics] The system identifies the genes encoding all proteins, transfer RNAs, ribosomal RNAs, in order to make initial functional assignments.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/bioinformatics] The GeneMark program trained to find protein-coding genes in *Haemophilus influenzae* is constantly changing and improving.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/bioinformatics] Following the goals that the Human Genome Project left to achieve after its closure in 2003, the ENCODE project was developed by the National Human Genome Research Institute.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/bioinformatics] While genome annotation is primarily based on sequence similarity (and thus homology), other properties of sequences can be used to predict the function of genes.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/bioinformatics] In fact, most *gene* function prediction methods focus on *protein* sequences as they are more informative and more feature-rich.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/bioinformatics] For instance, the distribution of hydrophobic amino acids predicts transmembrane segments in proteins.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/bioinformatics] However, protein function prediction can also use external information such as gene (or protein) expression data, protein structure, or protein–protein interactions.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/bioinformatics] Evolutionary biology is the study of the origin and descent of species, as well as their change over time.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/bioinformatics] The core of comparative genome analysis is the establishment of the correspondence between genes (orthology analysis) or other genomic features in different organisms.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/bioinformatics] Intergenomic maps are made to trace the evolutionary processes responsible for the divergence of two genomes.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/bioinformatics] A multitude of evolutionary events acting at various organizational levels shape genome evolution.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/bioinformatics] At the lowest level, point mutations affect individual nucleotides.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/bioinformatics] At a higher level, large chromosomal segments undergo duplication, lateral transfer, inversion, transposition, deletion and insertion.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/bioinformatics] Entire genomes are involved in processes of hybridization, polyploidization and endosymbiosis that lead to rapid speciation.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/bioinformatics] Many of these studies are based on the detection of sequence homology to assign sequences to protein families.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/bioinformatics] Pan genomics is a concept introduced in 2005 by Tettelin and Medini.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/bioinformatics] Pan genome is the complete gene repertoire of a particular monophyletic taxonomic group.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/bioinformatics] Although initially applied to closely related strains of a species, it can be applied to a larger context like genus, phylum, etc.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/bioinformatics] It is divided in two parts: the Core genome, a set of genes common to all the genomes under study (often housekeeping genes vital for survival), and the Dispensable/Flexible genome: a set of genes not present in all but one or some genomes under study.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/bioinformatics] A bioinformatics tool BPGA can be used to characterize the Pan Genome of bacterial species.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/bioinformatics] As of 2013, the existence of efficient high-throughput next-generation sequencing technology allows for the identification of cause many different human disorders.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/bioinformatics] Simple Mendelian inheritance has been observed for over 3,000 disorders that have been identified at the Online Mendelian Inheritance in Man database, but complex diseases are more difficult.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/bioinformatics] Association studies have found many individual genetic regions that individually are weakly associated with complex diseases (such as infertility, breast cancer and Alzheimer's disease), rather than a single cause.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/bioinformatics] There are currently many challenges to using genes for diagnosis and treatment, such as how we don't know which genes are important, or how stable the choices an algorithm provides.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/bioinformatics] Genome-wide association studies have successfully identified thousands of common genetic variants for complex diseases and traits; however, these common variants only explain a small fraction of heritability.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/bioinformatics] Rare variants may account for some of the missing heritability.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/bioinformatics] Large-scale whole genome sequencing studies have rapidly sequenced millions of whole genomes, and such studies have identified hundreds of millions of rare variants.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/bioinformatics] Functional annotations predict the effect or function of a genetic variant and help to prioritize rare functional variants, and incorporating these annotations can effectively boost the power of genetic association of rare variants analysis of whole genome sequencing studies.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/bioinformatics] Some tools have been developed to provide all-in-one rare variant association analysis for whole-genome sequencing data, including integration of genotype data and their functional annotations, association analysis, result summary and visualization.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/bioinformatics] Meta-analysis of whole genome sequencing studies provides an attractive solution to the problem of collecting large sample sizes for discovering rare variants associated with complex phenotypes.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/bioinformatics] In cancer, the genomes of affected cells are rearranged in complex or unpredictable ways.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/bioinformatics] In addition to single-nucleotide polymorphism arrays identifying point mutations that cause cancer, oligonucleotide microarrays can be used to identify chromosomal gains and losses (called comparative genomic hybridization).
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/bioinformatics] These detection methods generate terabytes of data per experiment.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/bioinformatics] The data is often found to contain considerable variability, or noise, and thus Hidden Markov model and change-point analysis methods are being developed to infer real copy number changes.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/bioinformatics] Two important principles can be used to identify cancer by mutations in the exome.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/bioinformatics] First, cancer is a disease of accumulated somatic mutations in genes.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/bioinformatics] Second, cancer contains driver mutations which need to be distinguished from passengers.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/bioinformatics] Further improvements in bioinformatics could allow for classifying types of cancer by analysis of cancer driven mutations in the genome.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/bioinformatics] Furthermore, tracking of patients while the disease progresses may be possible in the future with the sequence of cancer samples.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/bioinformatics] Another type of data that requires novel informatics development is the analysis of lesions found to be recurrent among many tumors.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/bioinformatics] All of these techniques are extremely noise-prone and/or subject to bias in the biological measurement, and a major research area in computational biology involves developing statistical tools to separate signal from noise in high-throughput gene expression studies.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/bioinformatics] Such studies are often used to determine the genes implicated in a disorder: one might compare microarray data from cancerous epithelial cells to data from non-cancerous cells to determine the transcripts that are up-regulated and down-regulated in a particular population of cancer cells.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/bioinformatics] Protein microarrays and high throughput (HT) mass spectrometry (MS) can provide a snapshot of the proteins present in a biological sample.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/bioinformatics] Cellular protein localization in a tissue context can be achieved through affinity proteomics displayed as spatial data based on immunohistochemistry and tissue microarrays.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/bioinformatics] Gene regulation is a complex process where a signal, such as an extracellular signal such as a hormone, eventually leads to an increase or decrease in the activity of one or more proteins.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/bioinformatics] Bioinformatics techniques have been applied to explore various steps in this process.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/bioinformatics] For example, gene expression can be regulated by nearby elements in the genome.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/bioinformatics] Promoter analysis involves the identification and study of sequence motifs in the DNA surrounding the protein-coding region of a gene.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/bioinformatics] These motifs influence the extent to which that region is transcribed into mRNA.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/bioinformatics] Enhancer elements far away from the promoter can also regulate gene expression, through three-dimensional looping interactions.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/bioinformatics] These interactions can be determined by bioinformatic analysis of chromosome conformation capture experiments.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/bioinformatics] Expression data can be used to infer gene regulation: one might compare microarray data from a wide variety of states of an organism to form hypotheses about the genes involved in each state.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/bioinformatics] In a single-cell organism, one might compare stages of the cell cycle, along with various stress conditions (heat shock, starvation, etc.).
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/bioinformatics] Clustering algorithms can be then applied to expression data to determine which genes are co-expressed.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/bioinformatics] For example, the upstream regions (promoters) of co-expressed genes can be searched for over-represented regulatory elements.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/bioinformatics] Examples of clustering algorithms applied in gene clustering are k-means clustering, self-organizing maps (SOMs), hierarchical clustering, and consensus clustering methods.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/bioinformatics] Several approaches have been developed to analyze the location of organelles, genes, proteins, and other components within cells.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/bioinformatics] A gene ontology category, *cellular component*, has been devised to capture subcellular localization in many biological databases.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/bioinformatics] Microscopic pictures allow for the location of organelles as well as molecules, which may be the source of abnormalities in diseases.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/bioinformatics] Finding the location of proteins allows us to predict what they do.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/bioinformatics] This is called protein function prediction.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/bioinformatics] For instance, if a protein is found in the nucleus it may be involved in gene regulation or splicing.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/bioinformatics] By contrast, if a protein is found in mitochondria, it may be involved in respiration or other metabolic processes.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/bioinformatics] There are well developed protein subcellular localization prediction resources available, including protein subcellular location databases, and prediction tools.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/bioinformatics] Data from high-throughput chromosome conformation capture experiments, such as Hi-C (experiment) and ChIA-PET, can provide information on the three-dimensional structure and nuclear organization of chromatin.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/bioinformatics] Bioinformatic challenges in this field include partitioning the genome into domains, such as Topologically Associating Domains (TADs), that are organised together in three-dimensional space.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/bioinformatics] Finding the structure of proteins is an important application of bioinformatics.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/bioinformatics] The Critical Assessment of Protein Structure Prediction (CASP) is an open competition where worldwide research groups submit protein models for evaluating unknown protein models.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/bioinformatics] The linear amino acid sequence of a protein is called the primary structure.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/bioinformatics] The primary structure can be easily determined from the sequence of codons on the DNA gene that codes for it.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/bioinformatics] In most proteins, the primary structure uniquely determines the 3-dimensional structure of a protein in its native environment.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/bioinformatics] An exception is the misfolded prion protein involved in bovine spongiform encephalopathy.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/bioinformatics] This structure is linked to the function of the protein.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/bioinformatics] Additional structural information includes the *secondary*, *tertiary* and *quaternary* structure.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/bioinformatics] A viable general solution to the prediction of the function of a protein remains an open problem.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/bioinformatics] Most efforts have so far been directed towards heuristics that work most of the time.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/bioinformatics] In the genomic branch of bioinformatics, homology is used to predict the function of a gene: if the sequence of gene *A*, whose function is known, is homologous to the sequence of gene *B,* whose function is unknown, one could infer that B may share A's function.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/bioinformatics] In structural bioinformatics, homology is used to determine which parts of a protein are important in structure formation and interaction with other proteins.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/bioinformatics] Homology modeling is used to predict the structure of an unknown protein from existing homologous proteins.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/bioinformatics] One example of this is hemoglobin in humans and the hemoglobin in legumes (leghemoglobin), which are distant relatives from the same protein superfamily.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/bioinformatics] Both serve the same purpose of transporting oxygen in the organism.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/bioinformatics] Although both of these proteins have very different amino acid sequences, their protein structures are very similar, reflecting their shared function and shared ancestor.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/bioinformatics] Other techniques for predicting protein structure include protein threading and *de novo* (from scratch) physics-based modeling.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/bioinformatics] Another aspect of structural bioinformatics include the use of protein structures for Virtual Screening models such as Quantitative Structure-Activity Relationship models and proteochemometric models (PCM).
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/bioinformatics] Furthermore, a protein's crystal structure can be used in simulation of for example ligand-binding studies and *in silico* mutagenesis studies.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/bioinformatics] A 2021 deep-learning algorithms-based software called AlphaFold, developed by Google's DeepMind, greatly outperforms all other prediction software methods, and has released predicted structures for hundreds of millions of proteins in the AlphaFold protein structure database.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/bioinformatics] A variety of methods have been developed to tackle the protein–protein docking problem, though it seems that there is still much work to be done in this field.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/bioinformatics] Other interactions encountered in the field include Protein–ligand (including drug) and protein–peptide.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/bioinformatics] Molecular dynamic simulation of movement of atoms about rotatable bonds is the fundamental principle behind computational algorithms, termed docking algorithms, for studying molecular interactions.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/bioinformatics] Biodiversity informatics deals with the collection and analysis of biodiversity data, such as taxonomic databases, or microbiome data.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/bioinformatics] Examples of such analyses include phylogenetics, niche modelling, species richness mapping, DNA barcoding, or species identification tools.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/bioinformatics] A growing area is also macro-ecology, i.e. the study of how biodiversity is connected to ecology and human impact, such as climate change.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/bioinformatics] The enormous number of published literature makes it virtually impossible for individuals to read every paper, resulting in disjointed sub-fields of research.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/bioinformatics] Literature analysis aims to employ computational and statistical linguistics to mine this growing library of text resources.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/bioinformatics] The area of research draws from statistics and computational linguistics.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/bioinformatics] Computational technologies are used to automate the processing, quantification and analysis of large amounts of high-information-content biomedical imagery.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/bioinformatics] Modern image analysis systems can improve an observer's accuracy, objectivity, or speed.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/bioinformatics] Image analysis is important for both diagnostics and research.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/bioinformatics] Computational techniques are used to analyse high-throughput, low-measurement single cell data, such as that obtained from flow cytometry.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/bioinformatics] These methods typically involve finding populations of cells that are relevant to a particular disease state or experimental condition.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/bioinformatics] Biological ontologies are directed acyclic graphs of controlled vocabularies.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/bioinformatics] They create categories for biological concepts and descriptions so they can be easily analyzed with computers.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/bioinformatics] When categorised in this way, it is possible to gain added value from holistic and integrated analysis.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/bioinformatics] The OBO Foundry was an effort to standardise certain ontologies.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/bioinformatics] One of the most widespread is the Gene ontology which describes gene function.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/bioinformatics] There are also ontologies which describe phenotypes.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/bioinformatics] Databases are essential for bioinformatics research and applications.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/bioinformatics] Databases exist for many different information types, including DNA and protein sequences, molecular structures, phenotypes and biodiversity.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/bioinformatics] Databases can contain both empirical data (obtained directly from experiments) and predicted data (obtained from analysis of existing data).
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/bioinformatics] They may be specific to a particular organism, pathway or molecule of interest.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/bioinformatics] Alternatively, they can incorporate data compiled from multiple other databases.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/bioinformatics] Databases can have different formats, access mechanisms, and be public or private.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/bioinformatics] Software tools for bioinformatics include simple command-line tools, more complex graphical programs, and standalone web-services.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/bioinformatics] They are made by bioinformatics companies or by public institutions.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/bioinformatics] Many free and open-source software tools have existed and continued to grow since the 1980s.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/bioinformatics] The open source tools often act as incubators of ideas, or community-supported plug-ins in commercial applications.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/bioinformatics] They may also provide *de facto* standards and shared object models for assisting with the challenge of bioinformation integration.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/bioinformatics] Open-source bioinformatics software includes Bioconductor, BioPerl, Biopython, BioJava, BioJS, BioRuby, Bioclipse, EMBOSS, .NET Bio, Orange with its bioinformatics add-on, Apache Taverna, UGENE and GenoCAD.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/bioinformatics] The non-profit Open Bioinformatics Foundation and the annual Bioinformatics Open Source Conference promote open-source bioinformatics software.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/bioinformatics] SOAP- and REST-based interfaces have been developed to allow client computers to use algorithms, data and computing resources from servers in other parts of the world.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/bioinformatics] The main advantage are that end users do not have to deal with software and database maintenance overheads.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/bioinformatics] Basic bioinformatics services are classified by the EBI into three categories: SSS (Sequence Search Services), MSA (Multiple Sequence Alignment), and BSA (Biological Sequence Analysis).
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/bioinformatics] A bioinformatics workflow management system is a specialized form of a workflow management system designed specifically to compose and execute a series of computational or data manipulation steps, or a workflow, in a Bioinformatics application.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/bioinformatics] Some of the platforms giving this service: Galaxy, Kepler, Taverna, UGENE, Anduril, HIVE.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/bioinformatics] In 2014, the US Food and Drug Administration sponsored a conference held at the National Institutes of Health Bethesda Campus to discuss reproducibility in bioinformatics.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/bioinformatics] Over the next three years, a consortium of stakeholders met regularly to discuss what would become BioCompute paradigm.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/bioinformatics] These stakeholders included representatives from government, industry, and academic entities.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/bioinformatics] It was decided that the BioCompute paradigm would be in the form of digital 'lab notebooks' which allow for the reproducibility, replication, review, and reuse, of bioinformatics protocols.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/bioinformatics] This was proposed to enable greater continuity within a research group over the course of normal personnel flux while furthering the exchange of ideas between groups.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/bioinformatics] The US FDA funded this work so that information on pipelines would be more transparent and accessible to their regulatory staff.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/bioinformatics] In 2016, the group reconvened at the NIH in Bethesda and discussed the potential for a BioCompute Object, an instance of the BioCompute paradigm.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/bioinformatics] This work was copied as both a "standard trial use" document and a preprint paper uploaded to bioRxiv.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/bioinformatics] The BioCompute object allows for the JSON-ized record to be shared among employees, collaborators, and regulators.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/bioinformatics] While bioinformatics is taught as an in-person master's degree at many universities, there are many other methods and technologies available to learn and obtain certification in the subject.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/bioinformatics] The computational nature of bioinformatics lends it to computer-aided and online learning.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/bioinformatics] Software platforms designed to teach bioinformatics concepts and methods include Rosalind and online courses offered through the Swiss Institute of Bioinformatics Training Portal.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/bioinformatics] The Canadian Bioinformatics Workshops provides videos and slides from training workshops on their website under a Creative Commons license.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/bioinformatics] The 4273π project or 4273pi project also offers open source educational materials for free.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/bioinformatics] The course runs on low cost Raspberry Pi computers and has been used to teach adults and school pupils.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/bioinformatics] 4273 is actively developed by a consortium of academics and research staff who have run research level bioinformatics using Raspberry Pi computers and the 4273π operating system.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/bioinformatics] There are several large conferences that are concerned with bioinformatics.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/bioinformatics] Some of the most notable examples are European Conference on Computational Biology (ECCB), Intelligent Systems for Molecular Biology (ISMB), Pacific Symposium on Biocomputing (PSB), and Research in Computational Molecular Biology (RECOMB).
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/bionumbers] The BioNumbers project performs literature-based curation of various sources.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/bionumbers] It is a regularly updated online resource that contains >13,000 entries from ~1,000 distinct references.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/bionumbers] Examples of data include transcription and translation rates, organism and organelle sizes, metabolites concentrations and growth rates.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/bionumbers] Entries are provided with full reference and details such as measurement method and comments.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/bionumbers] BioNumbers also publishes a monthly review of a problem in quantitative biology.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/bionumbers] BioNumbers was created as a Wikipedia-format community collaborative initiative in 2007 by Ron Milo, Paul Jorgensen and Mike Springer at the Systems Biology Department at Harvard Medical School.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/bionumbers] It is currently managed and curated at the Milo Lab from the Weizmann Institute of Science.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/bionumbers] The database is funded by the Systems Biology Department at Harvard Medical School, and Weizmann Institute of Science.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/blast-biotechnology] In bioinformatics, **BLAST** (**basic local alignment search tool**) is an algorithm and program for comparing primary biological sequence information, such as the amino-acid sequences of proteins, nucleotides of DNA and/or RNA sequences.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/blast-biotechnology] A BLAST search enables a researcher to compare a subject protein or nucleotide sequence (called a query) with a library or database of sequences, and identify database sequences that resemble the query sequence above a certain threshold.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/blast-biotechnology] For example, following the discovery of a previously unknown gene in the mouse, a scientist will typically perform a BLAST search of the human genome to see if humans carry a similar gene; BLAST will identify sequences in the human genome that resemble the mouse gene based on similarity of sequence.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/blast-biotechnology] BLAST is a widely used bioinformatics programs for sequence searching.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/blast-biotechnology] It addresses a fundamental problem in bioinformatics research.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/blast-biotechnology] The heuristic algorithm it uses is faster for large-scale searches compared to methods like Smith-Waterman.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/blast-biotechnology] This emphasis on speed is vital to making the algorithm practical on the huge genome databases currently available, although subsequent algorithms can be even faster.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/blast-biotechnology] The BLAST program was designed by Eugene Myers, Stephen Altschul, Warren Gish, David J.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/blast-biotechnology] Lipman and Webb Miller at the NIH and was published in J.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/blast-biotechnology] BLAST builds upon FASTA, a previously developed program for protein and DNA sequence similarity searches.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/blast-biotechnology] It incorporates a novel stochastic model developed by Samuel Karlin and Stephen Altschul.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/blast-biotechnology] While BLAST is faster than any Smith-Waterman implementation for most cases, it cannot "guarantee the optimal alignments of the query and database sequences" as Smith-Waterman algorithm does.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/blast-biotechnology] The Smith-Waterman algorithm was an extension of a previous optimal method, the Needleman–Wunsch algorithm, which was the first sequence alignment algorithm that was guaranteed to find the best possible alignment.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/blast-biotechnology] However, the time and space requirements of these optimal algorithms far exceed the requirements of BLAST.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/blast-biotechnology] BLAST is more time-efficient than FASTA by searching only for the more significant patterns in the sequences, yet with comparative sensitivity.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/blast-biotechnology] This could be further realized by understanding the algorithm of BLAST introduced below.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/blast-biotechnology] BLAST is also often used as part of other algorithms that require approximate sequence matching.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/blast-biotechnology] BLAST is available on the web on the NCBI website.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/blast-biotechnology] Different types of BLASTs are available according to the query sequences and the target databases.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/blast-biotechnology] Alternative implementations include AB-BLAST (formerly known as WU-BLAST), FSA-BLAST (last updated in 2006), and ScalaBLAST.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/blast-biotechnology] The original paper by Altschul, *et al.* was the most highly cited paper published in the 1990s.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/blast-biotechnology] Input sequences (in FASTA or Genbank format), database to search and other optional parameters such as scoring matrix.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/blast-biotechnology] BLAST output can be delivered in a variety of formats.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/blast-biotechnology] These formats include HTML, plain text, and XML formatting.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/blast-biotechnology] For NCBI's webpage, the default format for output is HTML.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/blast-biotechnology] When performing a BLAST on NCBI, the results are given in a graphical format showing the hits found, a table showing sequence identifiers for the hits with scoring related data, as well as alignments for the sequence of interest and the hits received with corresponding BLAST scores for these.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/blast-biotechnology] The easiest to read and most informative of these is probably the table.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/blast-biotechnology] If one is attempting to search for a proprietary sequence or simply one that is unavailable in databases available to the general public through sources such as NCBI, there is a BLAST program available for download to any computer, at no cost.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/blast-biotechnology] This can be found at BLAST+ executables.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/blast-biotechnology] There are also commercial programs available for purchase.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/blast-biotechnology] Databases can be found on the NCBI site, as well as on the Index of BLAST databases (FTP).
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/blast-biotechnology] Using a heuristic method, BLAST finds similar sequences, by locating short matches between the two sequences.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/blast-biotechnology] This process of finding similar sequences is called seeding.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/blast-biotechnology] It is after this first match that BLAST begins to make local alignments.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/blast-biotechnology] While attempting to find similarity in sequences, sets of common letters, known as words, are very important.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/blast-biotechnology] For example, suppose that the sequence contains the following stretch of letters, GLKFA.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/blast-biotechnology] If a BLAST was being conducted under normal conditions, the word size would be 3 letters.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/blast-biotechnology] In this case, using the given stretch of letters, the searched words would be GLK, LKF, and KFA.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/blast-biotechnology] The heuristic algorithm of BLAST locates all common three-letter words between the sequence of interest and the hit sequence or sequences from the database.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/blast-biotechnology] This result will then be used to build an alignment.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/blast-biotechnology] After making words for the sequence of interest, the rest of the words are also assembled.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/blast-biotechnology] These words must satisfy a requirement of having a score of at least the threshold *T*, when compared by using a scoring matrix.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/blast-biotechnology] One commonly used scoring matrix for BLAST searches is BLOSUM62, although the optimal scoring matrix depends on sequence similarity.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/blast-biotechnology] Once both words and neighborhood words are assembled and compiled, they are compared to the sequences in the database in order to find matches.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/blast-biotechnology] The threshold score *T* determines whether or not a particular word will be included in the alignment.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/blast-biotechnology] Once seeding has been conducted, the alignment which is only 3 residues long, is extended in both directions by the algorithm used by BLAST.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/blast-biotechnology] Each extension impacts the score of the alignment by either increasing or decreasing it.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/blast-biotechnology] If this score is higher than a pre-determined *T*, the alignment will be included in the results given by BLAST.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/blast-biotechnology] However, if this score is lower than this pre-determined *T*, the alignment will cease to extend, preventing the areas of poor alignment from being included in the BLAST results.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/blast-biotechnology] To run the software, BLAST requires a query sequence to search for, and a sequence to search against (also called the target sequence) or a sequence database containing multiple such sequences.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/blast-biotechnology] BLAST will find sub-sequences in the database which are similar to subsequences in the query.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/blast-biotechnology] In typical usage, the query sequence is much smaller than the database, e.g., the query may be one thousand nucleotides while the database is several billion nucleotides.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/blast-biotechnology] The main idea of BLAST is that there are often High-scoring Segment Pairs (HSP) contained in a statistically significant alignment.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/blast-biotechnology] BLAST searches for high scoring sequence alignments between the query sequence and the existing sequences in the database using a heuristic approach that approximates the Smith-Waterman algorithm.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/blast-biotechnology] However, the exhaustive Smith-Waterman approach is too slow for searching large genomic databases such as GenBank.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/blast-biotechnology] Therefore, the BLAST algorithm uses a heuristic approach that is less accurate than the Smith-Waterman algorithm but over 50 times faster.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/blast-biotechnology] The speed and relatively good accuracy of BLAST are among the technical innovations of the BLAST programs.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/blast-biotechnology] Key steps of the algorithm include filtering low-complexity regions, identifying high-scoring word matches, and statistically evaluating alignments.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/blast-biotechnology] *Make a*k*-letter word list of the query sequence.* Take *k*=3 for example, we list the words of length 3 in the query protein sequence (*k* is usually 11 for a DNA sequence) "sequentially", until the last letter of the query sequence is included.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/blast-biotechnology] *List the possible matching words.* This step is one of the main differences between BLAST and FASTA.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/blast-biotechnology] FASTA cares about all of the common words in the database and query sequences that are listed in step 2; however, BLAST only cares about the high-scoring words.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/blast-biotechnology] The scores are created by comparing the word in the list in step 2 with all the 3-letter words.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/blast-biotechnology] By using the scoring matrix (substitution matrix) to score the comparison of each residue pair, there are 20^3 possible match scores for a 3-letter word.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/blast-biotechnology] For example, the score obtained by comparing PQG with PEG and PQA is respectively 15 and 12 with the BLOSUM62 weighting scheme.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/blast-biotechnology] For DNA words, a match is scored as +5 and a mismatch as -4, or as +2 and -3.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/blast-biotechnology] After that, a neighborhood word score threshold *T* is used to reduce the number of possible matching words.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/blast-biotechnology] The words whose scores are greater than the threshold *T* will remain in the possible matching words list, while those with lower scores will be discarded.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/blast-biotechnology] For example, PEG is kept, but PQA is abandoned when T is 13.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/blast-biotechnology] *Organize the remaining high-scoring words into an efficient search tree.* This allows the program to rapidly compare the high-scoring words to the database sequences.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/blast-biotechnology] *Scan the database sequences for exact matches with the remaining high-scoring words.* The BLAST program scans the database sequences for the remaining high-scoring word, such as PEG, of each position.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/blast-biotechnology] If an exact match is found, this match is used to seed a possible un-gapped alignment between the query and database sequences.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/blast-biotechnology] *List all of the HSPs in the database whose score is high enough to be considered.* We list the HSPs whose scores are greater than the empirically determined cutoff score *S*.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/blast-biotechnology] By examining the distribution of the alignment scores modeled by comparing random sequences, a cutoff score *S* can be determined such that its value is large enough to guarantee the significance of the remaining HSPs.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/blast-biotechnology] *Evaluate the significance of the HSP score.* BLAST next assesses the statistical significance of each HSP score by exploiting the Gumbel extreme value distribution (EVD).
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/blast-biotechnology] (It is proved that the distribution of Smith-Waterman local alignment scores between two random sequences follows the Gumbel EVD.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/blast-biotechnology] For local alignments containing gaps it is not proved.).
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/blast-biotechnology] Note that $\lambda$ and $\mathrm {K}$ depend upon the substitution matrix, gap penalties, and sequence composition (the letter frequencies). $m'$ and $n'$ are the effective lengths of the query and database sequences, respectively.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/blast-biotechnology] The original sequence length is shortened to the effective length to compensate for the edge effect (an alignment start near the end of one of the query or database sequence is likely not to have enough sequence to build an optimal alignment).
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/blast-biotechnology] They can be calculated as $m'\approx m-{\frac {\ln Kmn}{H}}\;$ $n'\approx n-{\frac {\ln Kmn}{H}}\;$ where $\mathrm {H}$ is the average expected score per aligned pair of residues in an alignment of two random sequences.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/blast-biotechnology] Altschul and Gish gave the typical values, $\lambda =0.318$ , $\mathrm {K} =0.13$ , and $\mathrm {H} =0.40$ , for un-gapped local alignment using BLOSUM62 as the substitution matrix.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/blast-biotechnology] Using the typical values for assessing the significance is called the lookup table method; it is not accurate.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/blast-biotechnology] The expect score *E* of a database match is the number of times that an unrelated database sequence would obtain a score *S* higher than *x* by chance.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/blast-biotechnology] The calculation shown here is modified if individual HSPs are combined, such as when producing gapped alignments (described below), due to the variation of the statistical parameters.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/blast-biotechnology] *Make two or more HSP regions into a longer alignment.* Sometimes, we find two or more HSP regions in one database sequence that can be made into a longer alignment.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/blast-biotechnology] This provides additional evidence of the relation between the query and database sequence.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/blast-biotechnology] There are two methods, the Poisson method and the sum-of-scores method, to compare the significance of the newly combined HSP regions.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/blast-biotechnology] Suppose that there are two combined HSP regions with the pairs of scores (65, 40) and (52, 45), respectively.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/blast-biotechnology] The Poisson method gives more significance to the set with the maximal lower score (45>40).
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/blast-biotechnology] However, the sum-of-scores method prefers the first set, because 65+40 (105) is greater than 52+45(97).
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/blast-biotechnology] The original BLAST uses the Poisson method; gapped BLAST and the WU-BLAST uses the sum-of scores method.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/blast-biotechnology] BLASTn offers nucleotide to nucelotide searches.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/blast-biotechnology] This is useful when trying to identify evolutionary relationships between organisms.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/blast-biotechnology] tBLASTn used to carry out protein to translated DNA searches.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/blast-biotechnology] This is useful when looking for similar protein-coding regions in DNA sequences that haven't been fully annotated, like ESTs (short, single-read cDNA sequences) and HTGs (draft genome sequences).
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/blast-biotechnology] Since these sequences don't have known protein translations, we can only search for them using tBLASTn.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/blast-biotechnology] BLASTx compares a nucleotide query sequence (can be translated into six different protein sequences) against a protein database.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/blast-biotechnology] This tool is useful when the reading frame of the DNA sequence is uncertain or contains errors that might cause mistakes in protein-coding.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/blast-biotechnology] BLASTx provides combined statistics for hits across all frames, making it helpful for the initial analysis of new DNA sequences.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/blast-biotechnology] BLASTp, or Protein BLAST, is used to compare protein sequences.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/blast-biotechnology] You can input one or more protein sequences that you want to compare against a single protein sequence or a database of protein sequences.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/blast-biotechnology] This is useful when you're trying to identify a protein by finding similar sequences in existing protein databases.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/blast-biotechnology] Parallel BLAST versions of split databases are implemented using MPI and Pthreads, and have been ported to various platforms including Windows, Linux, Solaris, Mac OS X, and AIX.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/blast-biotechnology] Popular approaches to parallelize BLAST include query distribution, hash table segmentation, computation parallelization, and database segmentation (partition).
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/blast-biotechnology] Databases are split into equal sized pieces and stored locally on each node.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/blast-biotechnology] Each query is run on all nodes in parallel and the resultant BLAST output files from all nodes merged to yield the final output.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/blast-biotechnology] Specific implementations include MPIblast, ScalaBLAST, DCBLAST and so on.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/blast-biotechnology] MPIblast makes use of a database segmentation technique to parallelize the computation process.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/blast-biotechnology] This allows for significant performance improvements when conducting BLAST searches across a set of nodes in a cluster.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/blast-biotechnology] In some scenarios a superlinear speedup is achievable.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/blast-biotechnology] This makes MPIblast suitable for the extensive genomic datasets that are typically used in bioinformatics.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/blast-biotechnology] BLAST generally runs at a speed of O(n), where n is the size of the database.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/blast-biotechnology] The time to complete the search increases linearly as the size of the database increases.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/blast-biotechnology] MPIblast utilizes parallel processing to speed up the search.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/blast-biotechnology] The ideal speed for any parallel computation is a complexity of O(n/p), with n being the size of the database and p being the number of processors.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/blast-biotechnology] This would indicate that the job is evenly distributed among the p number of processors.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/blast-biotechnology] This is visualized in the included graph.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/blast-biotechnology] The superlinear speedup that can sometimes occur with MPIblast can have a complexity better than O(n/p).
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/blast-biotechnology] This occurs because the cache memory can be used to decrease the run time.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/blast-biotechnology] The predecessor to BLAST, FASTA, can also be used for protein and DNA similarity searching.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/blast-biotechnology] FASTA provides a similar set of programs for comparing proteins to protein and DNA databases, DNA to DNA and protein databases, and includes additional programs for working with unordered short peptides and DNA sequences.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/blast-biotechnology] In addition, the FASTA package provides SSEARCH, a vectorized implementation of the rigorous Smith-Waterman algorithm.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/blast-biotechnology] FASTA is slower than BLAST, but provides a much wider range of scoring matrices, making it easier to tailor a search to a specific evolutionary distance.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/blast-biotechnology] An extremely fast but considerably less sensitive alternative to BLAST is BLAT (*B*last *L*ike *A*lignment *T*ool).
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/blast-biotechnology] While BLAST does a linear search, BLAT relies on k-mer indexing the database, and can thus often find seeds faster.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/blast-biotechnology] Another software alternative similar to BLAT is PatternHunter.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/blast-biotechnology] Advances in sequencing technology in the late 2000s has made searching for very similar nucleotide matches an important problem.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/blast-biotechnology] New alignment programs tailored for this use typically use BWT-indexing of the target database (typically a genome).
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/blast-biotechnology] Input sequences can then be mapped very quickly, and output is typically in the form of a BAM file.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/blast-biotechnology] Example alignment programs are BWA, SOAP, and Bowtie.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/blast-biotechnology] For protein identification, searching for known domains (for instance from Pfam) by matching with Hidden Markov Models is a popular alternative, such as HMMER.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/blast-biotechnology] An alternative to BLAST for comparing two banks of sequences is PLAST.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/blast-biotechnology] PLAST provides a high-performance general purpose bank to bank sequence similarity search tool relying on the PLAST and ORIS algorithms.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/blast-biotechnology] Results of PLAST are very similar to BLAST, but PLAST is significantly faster and capable of comparing large sets of sequences with a small memory (i.e.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/blast-biotechnology] For applications in metagenomics, where the task is to compare billions of short DNA reads against tens of millions of protein references, DIAMOND runs at up to 20,000 times as fast as BLASTX, while maintaining a high level of sensitivity.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/blast-biotechnology] The open-source software MMseqs is an alternative to BLAST/PSI-BLAST, which improves on current search tools over the full range of speed-sensitivity trade-off, achieving sensitivities better than PSI-BLAST at more than 400 times its speed.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/blast-biotechnology] Optical computing approaches have been suggested as promising alternatives to the current electrical implementations.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/blast-biotechnology] OptCAM is an example of such approaches and is shown to be faster than BLAST.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/blast-biotechnology] While both Smith-Waterman and BLAST are used to find homologous sequences by searching and comparing a query sequence with those in the databases, they do have their differences.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/blast-biotechnology] Due to the fact that BLAST is based on a heuristic algorithm, the results received through BLAST will not include all the possible hits within the database.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/blast-biotechnology] An alternative in order to find all the possible hits would be to use the Smith-Waterman algorithm.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/blast-biotechnology] This method varies from the BLAST method in two areas, accuracy and speed.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/blast-biotechnology] The Smith-Waterman option provides better accuracy, in that it finds matches that BLAST cannot, because it does not exclude any information.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/blast-biotechnology] Therefore, it is necessary for remote homology.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/blast-biotechnology] However, when compared to BLAST, it is more time consuming and requires large amounts of computing power and memory.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/blast-biotechnology] However, advances have been made to speed up the Smith-Waterman search process dramatically.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/blast-biotechnology] These advances include FPGA chips and SIMD technology.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/blast-biotechnology] For more complete results from BLAST, the settings can be changed from their default settings.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/blast-biotechnology] The optimal settings for a given sequence, however, may vary.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/blast-biotechnology] The settings one can change are E-Value, gap costs, filters, word size, and substitution matrix.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/blast-biotechnology] Note, the algorithm used for BLAST was developed from the algorithm used for Smith-Waterman.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/blast-biotechnology] BLAST employs an alignment which finds "local alignments between sequences by finding short matches and from these initial matches (local) alignments are created".
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/blast-biotechnology] To help users interpreting BLAST results, different software is available.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/blast-biotechnology] Example visualizations of BLAST results are shown in Figure 4 and 5.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/blast-biotechnology] These include identifying species, locating domains, establishing phylogeny, DNA mapping, and comparison.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/blast-biotechnology] With the use of BLAST, you can possibly correctly identify a species or find homologous species.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/blast-biotechnology] This can be useful, for example, when you are working with a DNA sequence from an unknown species.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/blast-biotechnology] Using the results received through BLAST you can create a phylogenetic tree using the BLAST web-page.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/blast-biotechnology] methods, so should only be relied upon for "first pass" phylogenetic analyses.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/blast-biotechnology] When working with a known species, and looking to sequence a gene at an unknown location, BLAST can compare the chromosomal position of the sequence of interest, to relevant sequences in the database(s).
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/blast-biotechnology] NCBI has a "Magic-BLAST" tool built around BLAST for this purpose.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/blast-biotechnology] When working with genes, BLAST can locate common genes in two related species, and can be used to map annotations from one organism to another.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/blast-biotechnology] BLAST can use genetic sequences to compare multiple taxa against known taxonomical data.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/blast-biotechnology] By doing this, it can provide a picture of the evolutionary relationships between various species (Fig.6).
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/blast-biotechnology] , since if the gene shows up in an organism outside of the ancestral lineage, then it wouldn't be classified as an orphan gene.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/bowtie-sequence-analysis] The Bowtie sequence aligner was originally developed by Ben Langmead *et al.* at the University of Maryland in 2009.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/bowtie-sequence-analysis] The aligner is typically used with short reads and a large reference genome, or for whole genome analysis.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/bowtie-sequence-analysis] Bowtie conducts a quality-aware, greedy, randomized, depth-first search through the space of possible alignments.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/bowtie-sequence-analysis] Because the search is greedy, the first valid alignment encountered by Bowtie will not necessarily be the 'best' in terms of the number of mismatches or in terms of quality.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/bowtie-sequence-analysis] Bowtie is used as a sequence aligner by a number of other related bioinformatics algorithms, including TopHat, Cufflinks and the CummeRbund Bioconductor package.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/bowtie-sequence-analysis] On 16 October 2011, the developers released a beta fork of the project called **Bowtie 2**.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/bowtie-sequence-analysis] In addition to the Burrows-Wheeler transform, Bowtie 2 also uses an FM-index (similar to a suffix array) to keep its memory footprint small.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/bowtie-sequence-analysis] Due to its implementation, Bowtie 2 is more suited to finding longer, gapped alignments in comparison with the original Bowtie method.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/bowtie-sequence-analysis] There is no upper limit on read length in Bowtie 2 and it allows alignments to overlap ambiguous characters in the reference.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/broad-institute] The **Broad Institute of MIT and Harvard** (IPA: /broʊd/, pronunciation respelling: *BROHD*), or the **Broad Institute**, is a biomedical and genomic research center located in Cambridge, Massachusetts, United States.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/broad-institute] The institute is independently governed and supported as a 501(c)(3) nonprofit research organization under the name Broad Institute Inc., and it partners with the Massachusetts Institute of Technology, Harvard University, and the five Harvard teaching hospitals.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/broad-institute] The Broad Institute evolved from a decade of research collaborations among MIT and Harvard scientists.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/broad-institute] One cornerstone was the Center for Genome Research of the Whitehead Institute at MIT.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/broad-institute] Founded in 1982, the Whitehead Institute became a major center for genomics and the Human Genome Project.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/broad-institute] As early as 1995, scientists at the Whitehead started pilot projects in genomic medicine, forming an unofficial collaborative network among young scientists interested in genomic approaches to cancer and human genetics.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/broad-institute] Another cornerstone was the Institute of Chemistry and Cell Biology established by Harvard Medical School in 1998 to pursue chemical genetics as an academic discipline.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/broad-institute] Its screening facility was one of the first high-throughput resources opened in an academic setting.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/broad-institute] It facilitated small molecule screening projects for more than 80 research groups worldwide.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/broad-institute] The Broads made a founding gift of $100 million and the Broad Institute was formally launched in May 2004.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/broad-institute] In November 2005, the Broads announced an additional $100 million gift to the institute.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/broad-institute] On September 4, 2008, the Broads announced an endowment of $400 million to make the Broad Institute a permanent establishment.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/broad-institute] In November 2013, they invested an additional $100 million to fund a second decade of research at the institute.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/broad-institute] During the COVID-19 pandemic in the United States, the Broad Institute ran laboratory tests for the virus for about 100 colleges and universities in the northeastern U.S.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/broad-institute] As of September 2020, the Broad was processing one out of every 20 COVID-19 tests in the nation.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/broad-institute] The Broad Institute has 24 core faculty and 195 associate members from Harvard, MIT, and the Harvard-affiliated hospitals.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/broad-institute] The Broad Institute is made up of three types of organizational units: core member laboratories, research programs, and platforms.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/broad-institute] The Broad Institute's platforms are teams of professional scientists who focus on the discovery, development, and optimization of the technological tools that Broad and other researchers use to conduct research.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/broad-institute] The Broad Institute also supports the Data Visualization Initiative led by the Institute creative director Bang Wong, which is aimed at developing data visualizations to explore and communicate research findings.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/broad-institute] The faculty and staff of the Broad Institute include physicians, geneticists, and molecular, chemical, and computational biologists.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/broad-institute] The faculty currently includes 24 core members, whose labs are primarily located within the Broad Institute, and 195 associate members, whose primary labs are located at one of the universities or hospitals.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/broad-institute] The Broad Institute's facilities at 320 Charles Street in Cambridge, Massachusetts, house one of the largest genome sequencing centers in the world.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/broad-institute] As WICGR (Whitehead Institute/MIT Center for Genome Research), this facility was the largest contributor of sequence information to the Human Genome Project.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/broad-institute] In February 2006, The Broad Institute expanded to a new building at 415 Main Street, adjacent to the Whitehead Institute for Biomedical Research.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/broad-institute] This seven-story 231,000-square-foot (21,500 m2) building contains office, research laboratory, retail and museum space.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/broad-institute] It was designed by Architects Elkus Manfredi with Lab Planner McLellan Copenhagen and was awarded high honors by R&D Magazine.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/broad-institute] In 2011, the institute announced plans to construct an additional tower adjacent to the 415 Main Street site at 75 Ames Street.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/broad-institute] On May 21, 2014, the Broad officially inaugurated a 375,000-square-foot research building at 75 Ames Street in Cambridge's Kendall Square.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/broad-institute] The new facility has 15 floors, 11 of which are occupied, and has LEED gold certification.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/broad-institute] As of July 2014, it has around 800 occupants.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/broad-institute] Between 2009 and 2012, the operating revenue of the institute was approximately $200 million, with 55% of that coming from federal grants.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/broad-institute] The Broad Foundation (Eli and Edythe Broad) has provided $700 million in funding to the Broad Institute as of February 2014.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/broad-institute] The Klarman Family Foundation provided a $32.5 million grant to Broad to study cellular processes in 2012.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/broad-institute] In October 2013, Fundación Carlos Slim (the Carlos Slim Foundation) of Mexico announced a $74 million grant to Broad Institute for the SIGMA2 consortium.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/broad-institute] In July 2014, coinciding with the publication of a new study on the genetics of schizophrenia, the Broad Institute received a $650 million gift from the Stanley Family Foundation, one of the largest private gifts ever for scientific research.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/broad-institute] On October 10, 2017, it was reported that Deerfield Management Co. was giving $50 million to the Broad Institute of MIT and Harvard to support biology research.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/broad-institute] Richard Merkin has been donating since 2009 in support of research, founding the Merkin Institute for Transformative Technologies in Healthcare.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/broad-institute] Dedicated on October 6, 2021, The Broad Institute's new building at 415 Main Street in Cambridge, Massachusetts was named the Richard N.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/broad-institute] Since 2010, the Broad Institute has been listed on *The Boston Globe'*s Top Places to Work.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/broad-institute] The 2014 report from Thomson Reuters' ScienceWatch entitled "The World's Most Influential Scientific Minds" recognized that 12 out of the 17 "hottest" researchers in science belonged to genomics, and 4 out of the top 5 were affiliated with the Broad Institute.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/broad-institute] Gabriel of the Broad Institute topped this entire list.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/broad-institute] Twenty-eight researchers from Broad Institute have been recognized on ISI's Highly Cited, a database that recognizes the top 250 researchers in multiple areas of science.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/broad-institute] Scolnick are members of the National Academy of Sciences and the Institute of Medicine.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/broad-institute] David Altshuler is a member of the Institute of Medicine.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/broad-institute] Waterman Award from the National Science Foundation.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/broad-institute] In biochemistry, genetics, and molecular biology areas, the institute was ranked #1 in the "Mapping Excellence" report, a survey that assessed high-impact publications.
[src:barcode-of-life-data-system/broad-institute] For its architecture, Broad's 415 Main Street building architects Elkus Manfredi Architects of Boston and AHSC McLellan Copenhagen of San Francisco received high honors in the 2007 Laboratory of the Year competition of the R&D Magazine.
